From 735f9b9aa4af50bcaa0758a608ff67c0378a9c9c Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Vasu Bhatia <git@vbh.ai>
Date: Thu, 30 Apr 2026 14:57:49 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] eink: drive Compose-pipeline battery colours to pure B/W
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The previous patch flipped colours on BatteryDrawableState (the
pre-Compose unified rendering), but that path is gated by the
new_status_bar_icons aconfig flag which is unset on this build —
defaults to disabled, so that file is dead code today.

The actually-live battery rendering on this build is the Compose
pipeline at statusbar/pipeline/battery/shared/ui/BatteryColors.kt.
Same set of hardcoded colours (Charging=#18CC47 green, Error=#FF0E01
red, PowerSave=#FFC917 yellow), same fix: drive them to pure black
in LightTheme and pure white in DarkTheme. State communicated via
the layered glyph (lightning bolt / '+' overlay), level-bar height,
and the system notification path.

The faint-grey level-meter backgrounds (lowAlphaBg = 20% black,
highAlphaBg = 55% black) are deliberately kept as alpha-on-white.
Strict B/W would flip them opaque white, but then the unfilled
portion of the meter vanishes against the white status bar and the
level becomes unreadable. Same pragmatic exception as the disabled
QS tile grey from Stage 0 — localised to a small icon.

The previous BatteryDrawableState patch is kept as defensive
coverage for if/when the aconfig flag flips on upstream.

Change-Id: Ic866dcc916dd63cc8d055ca39da3b17e984a1e87
---
 .../battery/shared/ui/BatteryColors.kt        | 23 ++++++++++++++-----
 1 file changed, 17 insertions(+), 6 deletions(-)

diff --git a/packages/SystemUI/src/com/android/systemui/statusbar/pipeline/battery/shared/ui/BatteryColors.kt b/packages/SystemUI/src/com/android/systemui/statusbar/pipeline/battery/shared/ui/BatteryColors.kt
index a1675766ba04..2c19bf1c0b92 100644
--- a/packages/SystemUI/src/com/android/systemui/statusbar/pipeline/battery/shared/ui/BatteryColors.kt
+++ b/packages/SystemUI/src/com/android/systemui/statusbar/pipeline/battery/shared/ui/BatteryColors.kt
@@ -63,16 +63,24 @@ sealed interface BatteryColors {
             override val backgroundWithGlyph = highAlphaBg
         }
 
+        // E-Ink: drop the green/red/yellow level fills — EPD has no useful colour
+        // reproduction and ages unevenly with sustained green/red/yellow pixels. State
+        // is communicated by the layered glyph/attribution (lightning bolt while
+        // charging, '+' while battery-saver), the level-bar height itself, and the
+        // system notification path for critical battery. The faint-grey backgrounds
+        // (lowAlphaBg / highAlphaBg) are kept — they are local to a small icon and
+        // provide the "unfilled portion" cue that pure white would erase against the
+        // white status bar; same pragmatic exception we made for disabled QS tiles.
         data object Charging : LightTheme() {
-            override val fill = Color(0xFF18CC47)
+            override val fill = Color.Black
         }
 
         data object Error : LightTheme() {
-            override val fill = Color(0xFFFF0E01)
+            override val fill = Color.Black
         }
 
         data object PowerSave : LightTheme() {
-            override val fill = Color(0xFFFFC917)
+            override val fill = Color.Black
         }
 
         companion object {
@@ -99,16 +107,19 @@ sealed interface BatteryColors {
             override val fill = Color.White
         }
 
+        // E-Ink: same B/W rationale as LightTheme above. Dark theme should never run
+        // on EPD (white-on-black ghosts heavily) but kept consistent for safety in
+        // case dark mode is toggled.
         data object Charging : DarkTheme() {
-            override val fill = Color(0xFF18CC47)
+            override val fill = Color.White
         }
 
         data object Error : DarkTheme() {
-            override val fill = Color(0xFFFF0E01)
+            override val fill = Color.White
         }
 
         data object PowerSave : DarkTheme() {
-            override val fill = Color(0xFFFFC917)
+            override val fill = Color.White
         }
 
         companion object {
